<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence from the Charity Finance Group [CEP0015]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Executive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Charity Finance Group welcomes the opportunity to respond to this call for evidence on charity Chief Executive pay. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CFG works with finance professionals to enable them to give the essential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">financial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">leadership that their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">charities need; it is ess</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ential that charities are financially confident and trustworthy in decision making, including on pay.  We summarise our views in this submission as follows:</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are a number of features specific to the charity sector that influence employment and pay of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">staff.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> These include the variation inherent to the sector in terms of size, organisation type and activity, as well as bespoke features of the labour market. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Trustees, usually unpaid volunteers, are ‘entrusted’ with the resources of the charity in accor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dance with achieving its mission.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It is the trustees’ responsibility to determine the policy for payment of a charity’s staff and the pay of the Chief Executive Officer. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This can be highly complex.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In making this decision</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> trustees will consider a range of factors such as skills and experience required. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Staff costs are an important aspect of charitable expenditure. Access to a high quality and professional labour market is critical to a thriving sector. CFG supports the s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">trengthening of professional skills in the sector to ensure that high standards of management and stewardship are upheld. We note that sector pay generally is comparatively lower than in other sectors and that the recession has had significant effect on sa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lary levels which have not generally kept pace with inflation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Transparency is an essential element of building accountability but cannot be done with provision of more information alone.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It is important that charities are required to produce genuinely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> useful information with adequate context.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The transparency of charities in relation to staff pay is often misunderstood.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> CFG highlights that under the SORP charities are required to publish wide ranging information on staff pay.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We feel this could be e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nhanced further by adding contextual information in the form of details of the remuneration policy.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As independent bodies charities are closer in terms of structure and governance to corporate entities, with many governed by both charity and company law</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Charity reporting requirements relating to staff pay go beyond those of comparatively sized companies. This is important due to the public accountability requirements charities fall under, but should remain proportionate to the scale of the organisation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and should not lead to unnecessary reporting.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#c6d9f1; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">About Charity Finance Group </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Charity Finance Group works at inspiring the development of a financially confident, dynamic and trustworthy charity sector. CFG works with finance professionals to enable them to give the essential leadership on finance strategy and management that their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">charities need; promoting best practice in charity finance, driving up standards, campaigning for a better operating environment and ensuring every pound given to charity works harder and that the trust of charity donors is maintained. CFG has more than 2,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">200 members, all senior finance professionals working in the sector and collectively our members are responsible for the management of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> over £19bn in charitable funds.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CFG supports a professional sector; it is essential that professional skills are utilised to ensure that there is good stewardship of charitable income, high quality strategic decision making and use of governance and accountability mechanisms.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#c6d9f1; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Feature</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s underpinning employment in charities</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Variation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The term ‘charity’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is used to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a wide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> range of organisational types, siz</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e, business model and activity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are approximately 163,000 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">charities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> registered with the Charity Commission for England an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Of these, we estimate around 20,000 employ staff.  The vas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t majority of charities are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> small</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; nearly 90% have an income below £500,000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">When reflecting on the pay professionals in the charity sector it is important to consider the heterogeneous </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nature of the organisations within it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Scale</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scale </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a core factor influencing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the employment of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> staff; as organisations scale up it becomes essential to bring in employees to ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">intain services.  There are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">roles which can only be d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">one on a sustai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nable basis by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> employee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">specific </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">qualifications or skills</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and which may require more particular remuneration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Labour market:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Access to a high quality labour market is very important to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">achieving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an active</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> thri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ving sector.  This is true </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for volunteers and staff, both of which are essential to delivering charitable services.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">here will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">always be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a broad range of subjective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">views on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">how senior professionals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be paid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in charities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In a tough </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">economic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">climate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> payment and reward is particularly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a contentious</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> subject.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Research has shown that the public feel that lower salaries would be desirable in a number of different public and private leadership roles.  It has also shown a significant gap between the percep</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion and reality of pay awards</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#c6d9f1; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Determining staff pay in charities</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The role of the trustees </span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is the role and responsibility of the trustees to determine the pay of the CEO.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Under charity law t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rustees are ‘entrusted’ with the resources of the charity in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accordance with achieving their mission.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is a highly complex task and a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> range of factors will be considered as part of the remuneration policy for the chief executive role.  These may inclu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, but are not exclusive to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The type and level of experience required of a candidate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Desired skills;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Desired qualifications</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Comparatives with other similar organisations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in or outside of the charity sector;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The range of sectors or other types organisations from which candidates are to be attracted; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Experience of managing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">high number of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">personnel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Understanding of the risks facing the organisation.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is best practice to implement processes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for regular review of staff levels and pay. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Many larger organisations for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have a remuneration committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> responsible for reviewing pay on a yearly basis.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Where appropriate, decisions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">may be taken </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in discussion with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">relevant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">management team</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s but will be the ultimate responsibility </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the trustee board.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Pay in charities</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK charity sector employed approximately 732,000 staff in 2011, 2.6% of the UK workforce. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Evidence shows that a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">verage l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evels of pay in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> UK charity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lower th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an in the private or public sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The pay gap between the highest and lowest paid is also smaller tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n in other sectors</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Overall staff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> costs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as a proportion of charity expenditure are fairly consistent across charities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of different sizes -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">around </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">40%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  This suggests that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">larger salaries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for senior roles in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">charities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with bigger incomes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are not skewing the cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of employing staff, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and that the expenditure remains proportionate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Recent research has also shown that in the largest charities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> pay </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">among </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CEOs correlates strongly with rising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> income and with overall staff costs</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">organisational </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">income is not, and should not be, the only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">performance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">factor influencing pay award for charity professionals.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The recession has had an impact on s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ector pay</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> generally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and senior </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">employees </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have not been exempt from this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CFG salary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> survey</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, a useful benchmarking tool for our members,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as shown that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> pay </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">among finance professionals in the sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">remained fa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">irly static</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> since 2009</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">here </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">only</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">been a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">slight increase in salary for our members but this is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lower than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inflation</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Similarly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">organisation-wide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cost of living pay awards in the sector have not been increasing, and in the half of charities that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have offered them, the amount was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> below inflation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  CEO’s pay seems to have been affected in a similar way</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, with a dip in 2012 and a subsequent rise, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bringing average pay back to 2011 levels</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">rofessional sector</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a charity becomes larger, gains profile and reaches into new service ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eas, the responsibility and expectations of donors and other stakeholders grows with it.  In this context it is essential that the charity is able to uphold these expectations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the actions of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> professional staff.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CFG’s research into financial management in smaller charities has identified that below </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a £500,000 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">income charities are unli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">kely to have staff with specialised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> financial skills</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and may rely on external advice to ensure they are meeting standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of good pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">actice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This can be expensive if the right support cannot be found on a voluntary basis.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Between £500,000 and £1m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">income</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">complexity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of financial management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is likely to increase,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and with it the requirements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for financial accountability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> become more on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erous.  At this stage it becomes more likely t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat charities will look to bring</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> higher level financial skills in-house if they can afford to do so. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For example, it may be beneficial to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">employ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a qualified</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> individual who can manage th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e relationship with the a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uditor</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Larger charities, responsible for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">income</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and complexity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">likely to require mor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e management staff </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and a broader range</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">experience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> large international charity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, with over £100m in income, a number of international </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">offices and hundreds of local partners,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">need a Finance D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">irector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">high level of skills and experience </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to manage the risks, scale and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">complexity in order</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to meet </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strategic demands.  The same organisation may al</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">so require </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">finance profession</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">als </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> focussed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">responsibilities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in order to ensure tight financial management of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">national and international operatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ns, trading arms,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> internal audit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, payroll and budgeting, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">functions essential in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the charity’s effectiveness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Si</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nce the recession, the sector has seen increased movement of financial management personnel between sectors, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with many moving into charities from the private sector</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Comparisons between our own data and that of ICAEW shows that finance director roles in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the private sector attract significantly greater pay.  We know that a driving factor for individuals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> choosing to work in charities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on the other hand the ethos of the sector;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for this reason pay is less</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> significant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">motive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it may be for other jo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bs.  This comes with a ‘reasonable’ caveat as individuals generally cannot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> dramatically forego potential income.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#c6d9f1; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Reporting in charities</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">importance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">of transparency</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Charities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are accountable to a number of stakeholders. It is important that these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stakeholders are able to hold charities to account on the decisions that they make</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, including decisions on pay</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are common misconceptions on the transparency of charities when it comes to staff pay.  In fact there is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">good level </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of information av</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ailable in charities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Trustees</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Annual Report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and Accounts.  For larger charities, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it is common practice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stakeholders </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be able to identify the number of staff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> earning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">higher salaries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (above £60,000)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he importance of staff in delivering charitab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">le objectives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be misunderstood</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ssumption</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aff in charities should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> earn lower amounts are based on a desire to direct </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as much money as possible to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cause</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould state that paying for the activity carried out by paid staff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is one of the most important aspects of charitable expenditure on the cause</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the two cannot be disassociated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Transparency is not just about how much information is provided, it is also important that information is coherent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">context.  There has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">been a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> push in financial reporting to remove unnecessary clutter from the accounts and this has led to a number of debates among charities as to what information is useful and should be reported, and what is not. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Staff pay has been considered in particular in this context.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">General r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">eporting requirements for charities</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One of the main routes through which the accountability of any organisa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion is addressed is through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> financial reporting.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All charities with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an inco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">me of over £25,000 are expected to complete an Annual Return and send it to the Charity Commission along with a Trustees’ Annual Report and Accounts.  Charities with an income above £250,000 are required to file accounts compliant with the Charities Statem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent of Recommended Practice (SORP) which interprets financial reporting standards for charities.  A new version of the Charities SORP was consulted on in 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to which CFG submitted a response</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are charities required to disclose on pay?</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Disclosure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">xecutive remuneration can be considered in two different contexts, that relating to trustees, and that relating to staff.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The board of trustees:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Charities are required to publish any trustees’ expenses along with the nature of those expenses in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">notes to the accounts. Expenses relate to costs incurred</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> trustee’s services to the char</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ity. The Charity Commission on occasion approves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the payment of trustees for their role.  In these circumstances this would also need to be disclosed.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Employees:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">harities are required to publish their staff costs in full in the notes to the accounts.  This should be split between gross wages and salaries, employer’s national insurance and pension costs. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Charities also provide the number of full time equivalent staf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f, and are advised to split this in to sub-categories dependent on how they split their activities.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Specific information on staff pay:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Charities with an income above £500,000 are sub</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ject to statutory audit and are subject to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> greater transparency require</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ments.  For these charities the number of employees with total remuneration within each band of £10,000 above £60,000 must be disclosed.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This means that for larger charities stakeholders are able to get a good overview of the number of staff on higher salaries and therefore the general approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">employed on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> staff pay.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is our view that revealing further information on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">individual</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s sa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> adds little to real transparency beyond the symbolic, and may actually be misleading when not considered in the context of broader infor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mation on staff pay.  H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owever</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">many large charities choose to do this anyway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by publishing the exact salary of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CEO. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his is a decision of the individual board of trustees depending on what they feel is in the best interests of the organisation. For example, some feel that disclosing the job title and salary of the highest paid member of staff may be an issue of int</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ernal sensitivity.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  If above £60,000 this will always be identifiable to within £10,000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> due to the requirements outlined in paragraph 29</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">CFG recommended in our 2013 SORP response that larger charities should be asked to provide details of their remuner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ation policy in their annual report in order to enhance the context of published figures</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Comparisons with other sectors</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is widely accepted that charitable status does increase </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the need for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">public accountability, and charities take</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> responsibility to uphold high standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> seriously.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The board of trustees</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are different to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the directors </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of many corporate entities where the board </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also benefit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from the remuneration decisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sually charity trustees are volunteers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Governance processes designed for the corporate sector are therefore not directly transferrable.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Listed companies</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Disclosure for listed companies is governed largely by International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRS)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the UK Good Governance Code </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> company law.  Recent amendments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to company law are intended to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> strengthen </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accountability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to shareholders.  This has included reference to a new ‘single figure’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for director remuneration, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">designed to remove some of the complexity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for shareholders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deciphering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">opaque </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">remuneration packages. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">issues are slightly different among smaller companies and charities, where pay and other benefits are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> far</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> less complex. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Similarly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for listed companies re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">quirements are being developed so that executive pay i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s to be compared </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with performance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (usually in terms of profit)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  This is clearly not transferrable to the charity context where performance should be judged on very different indicators</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and may be highly subjective due to the personal connection many stake</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">holders feel with the cause</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Where in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">come may be one </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">indicator</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">charity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, achievements against </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mission and objectives are the most important element</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of performance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  These are typically </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">difficult to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">proportionately </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">measure and report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Smaller </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">companies</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Smaller companies of a closely comparable size to charities are now required to refer to ‘key management personnel’ and to disclose compensation in total but not for individuals.  The reference to ‘key management personnel’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">does not easily transf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to the charity sector.  We would also note that charities disclose far more than these private sector counterparts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of a similar size due to the guidelines in the Charity SORP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as outlined in the above section. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Public sector</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ublic bodies are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">now </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">expected to release information on any individu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al earning more that £150,000.  The sheer size and complexity of the public sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">alters ou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r access to and understanding this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> information dramatically.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Often charities are compared with the public sector bec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ause they are considered publicly accountable a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">since </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">they work in services which are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> also som</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">etimes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> provided by the state</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  However, in terms of governance charities are more like </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">independent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">corporate entities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lthough many of the same arguments will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be used </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">around staff pay, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in terms of attracting skills and quality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> both the public and charity sectors, the context and accountability structures are different</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Drawing comparison with other high-profile positions in the public sector is also fairly arbitrary and serves as little other than symbolic in demonstrating factors which should influence senior pay in big charities.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#c6d9f1; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Concluding remarks</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his is clearly an important issue relating to public trust and confidence in the sector, something we aim to enhance.  It is essential that debates on this area, and others, consider the full range of information and influencing factors.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would urge the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Committee to consider closely the points we have raised here, along with the evidence provided by other sector representatives on this issue.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> nfpSynergy Charity Awareness Monitor 2012 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> NCVO Voluntary Sector Workforce Almanac 2013 (analysing figures from 2011)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> NfpSynergy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> ‘Fat Cats or Top Dogs: charity CEO salaries’ 2013 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> CFG Salary Survey 2013 (compared with previous years)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> ACEVO CEO pay survey 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> CFG ‘Making it Count’ 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> CFG Salary Survey 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> www.charitysorp.org</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span styl